=== EDGE FUNCTIONS & DATABASE MIGRATIONS (MANDATORY) ===

Even without a Supabase project connected, you MUST create the correct files when the task requires them:

EDGE FUNCTIONS - create supabase/functions/<function-name>/index.ts for:
- LLM/AI features (chat, completions, embeddings, vector search)
- Third-party API integrations (Stripe, SendGrid, Twilio, OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.)
- Incoming webhooks from external services
- Any server-only logic or logic that must not expose secrets to the client
- Any prompt that says "create edge function" or "add edge function"
File location: supabase/functions/<function-name>/index.ts
Import pattern: import { serve } from "https://deno.land/std@0.168.0/http/server.ts";
Never expose API keys or secrets in client-side code.

DATABASE MIGRATIONS - create supabase/migrations/<YYYYMMDDHHmmss>_<description>.sql for:
- Every new database table, view, or enum mentioned in the task
- Every schema change (ALTER TABLE, new index, new policy, etc.)
- Any prompt that says "create migration" or describes a data model
Make migrations idempotent (IF NOT EXISTS / CREATE OR REPLACE). Include RLS policies.
Do NOT run "supabase db push" or execute SQL directly — only create the .sql files.

MANDATORY CHECKLIST - Before finishing, verify:
- [ ] Migration SQL file(s) created for every database table/schema change mentioned
- [ ] Edge Function file(s) created for every server-side/secrets feature mentioned
- [ ] TypeScript types created for every new database table

=== TASK ===
# Search & Filter

## Overview
Implement a robust Search & Filter subsystem to enable full-text search and faceted filtering across entities: companies, reports, and users. Features include autosuggest, fast query performance, result ranking, debounced search, and client-side caching. Ensure all results are safely handled with runtime guards (null/undefined) and that Supabase results are normalized with data ?? [] patterns. This component must integrate cleanly with authentication, authorization, and the core data model established for PulseBoard. The goal is to empower users to quickly locate relevant records, refine results with multi-criteria filters, and select items to view details or perform actions (e.g., open report, edit company, manage user roles).

## Components to Build
1) Global Search Bar with Autosuggest
- Debounced input (e.g., 250ms) triggers incremental search across entities.
- Autosuggest dropdown with categorized suggestions: Companies, Reports, Users.
- Highlight matching segments; keyboard navigation (↑/↓, Enter to select); accessible ARIA roles.
- Clear button and focus management; loading indicator.

2) Faceted Filter Panel
- Multi-select and toggle filters for: status, industry, health score bands, last analyzed date, owner/creator, tags, and search scope (companies/reports/users).
- Numeric range sliders (e.g., health score 0-100, date range).
- Text search field integration (must work with autosuggest and full-text search).
- Persist filter state in URL query parameters for shareable links and restore on page load.

3) Results Grid / List Components
- Consistent card/list items for Companies, Reports, and Users.
- Safe rendering with data guards; all lists derived from results with (data ?? []) pattern.
- Infinite or paginated results with client-side cursor-based pagination if needed; support “Load more” or automatic fetch on scroll.

4) Detail & Actions Drawer/Panel
- When a result is selected, open a detail panel (drawer or modal) with read/write actions based on user permissions.
- Actions include: Open detail page, Edit, Delete (soft delete with confirmation), Export (CSV/JSON), or Run Analysis (for reports).

5) Performance & Caching Layer
- Client-side caching of recent search results (e.g., useMemo/useState with proper guards); invalidation on mutations.
- Debounced fetch with cancellation tokens to prevent race conditions.
- Ensure all array operations guard against nullish values: (items ?? []).map(...)

6) Backend Helpers & API Integration
- Supabase-backed search endpoints with proper RLS (Row Level Security) constraints.
- Endpoints to support: /search (POST) with query and filters; /search/autosuggest (GET) based on input; /search/preview (GET) for lightweight previews.
- Server-side ranking: prioritize exact matches, then partial matches, then recent activity, then user-owned items.

7) Accessibility & Internationalization
- Keyboard-first navigation, focus trapping in drawers.
- i18n-ready text strings and pluralization in UI.

8) Testing Utilities
- Mock data builders for companies, reports, users.
- Test helpers to simulate empty results, partial/malformed API responses.
- E2E tests outline (Cypress/Playwright) for search with autosuggest, filters, and result selection.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React with TypeScript (or your project’s standard).
- State management: useState/useEffect; optional useReducer for complex flows; if you use a global store, ensure integration points are explicit.
- Hooks:
  - useDebouncedValue(value, delay) to handle autosuggest timing.
  - useSortablePagination for results if needed.
- UI components:
  - Autocomplete/autosuggest component with keyboard support and accessibility attributes.
  - Multi-select chip filters with clear actions.
  - Range slider components (min/max values) with accessible labels.
  - Card/List components for search results, with null-safety for data fields.
  - Detail Drawer/Modal with action buttons conditioned on permissions.
- Data handling:
  - All API responses validated: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Supabase results normalized: const items = data ?? [].
  - Guard any property access: obj?.property?.nested.
- Performance:
  - Debounced search, cancellable requests, and minimal re-renders.
  - Prefetch common queries (e.g., popular industries) to improve perceived speed.
- Accessibility:
  - ARIA roles, aria-expanded attributes for dropdowns, keyboard nav, focus management.

### Backend
- Endpoints (REST or GraphQL, aligned to project standards):
  - POST /api/search
    - Body: { query: string, scope: 'companies'|'reports'|'users'|'all', filters: FilterPayload, pagination?: { page, pageSize } }
    - Returns: { data: Item[], count: number }
  - GET /api/search/autosuggest?input=...
    - Returns: { companies: Item[], reports: Item[], users: Item[] }
  - GET /api/search/preview?id=...
    - Returns lightweight fields for quick preview; validated with default values.
- Database schema notes:
  - Companies: id, name, industry, healthScore, etc.
  - Reports: id, companyId, title, createdAt, summary.
  - Users: id, name, email, role, etc.
  - Search vectors: maintain tsvector for PostgreSQL full-text search if using PG full-text indexing; or leverage Supabase's FTS capabilities.
- Functions:
  - Build dynamic SQL or FTS queries with safety against SQL injection via parameterized queries.
  - Enforce permission checks on data returned (only items visible to current user).
- Performance:
  - Create composite indexes for search fields (name/title, industry, owner, tags) and for filters (healthScore, lastAnalzyedAt).
  - Use server-side pagination and limit results to a reasonable cap.

### Integration
- Auth & Access:
  - Ensure all search results are filtered by user’s permissions using RLS or explicit checks in API layer.
  - Respect roles: admins can see all; regular users see owned/accessible items only.
- Data Flow:
  - UI dispatches search requests; API returns data validated to arrays; UI renders with guarded mappings.
  - Actions in detail panel trigger mutations (edit/delete) and automatically refresh relevant search lists.
- Consistency:
  - Use a single canonical data shape for items: { id: string, type: 'company'|'report'|'user', title: string, subtitle?: string, snippets?: string[], updatedAt?: string, ... }.
  - Normalize dates to ISO strings; handle nulls gracefully.

## User Experience Flow
1) User lands on Dashboard with a focus on their single company (per project: see the Dashboard page). If no company exists, show a prominent CTA to create a company.
2) User focuses the global search bar at top; begins typing.
3) Autosuggest dropdown appears with categorised results (Companies, Reports, Users). User can navigate via keyboard or mouse; selects an item to open its detail page.
4) User applies filters via the facet panel (e.g., filter companies by industry, health score 60-90, last analyzed within 30 days). URL updates to reflect filters.
5) Results grid updates in real-time; user can paginate or infinite-scroll through results.
6) User clicks a result to view details in a drawer or modal; performs permissible actions (edit, export, etc.). Mutations trigger UI refresh of lists.
7) User can clear filters and/or reset search; state returns to default; URL query params reset.
8) All interactions guard against null/undefined results; UI gracefully handles empty states with helpful messages and CTAs.

